00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:09,385
CHAPTER XXXII CETOLOGY Already we are boldly launched upon the deep, but soon we shall be lost in its unshored, harborless immensities.

2
00:00:09,686 --> 00:00:17,618
E'er that come to pass, e'er the Pequod's weedy hull rolls side by side with the barnacled hulls of the Leviathan.

3
00:00:18,138 --> 00:00:31,767
At the outset it is but well to attend to a matter almost indispensable to a thorough appreciative understanding of the more special Leviathanic revelations and allusions of all sorts which are to follow.

4
00:00:32,388 --> 00:00:37,800
It is some systematized exhibition of the whale in his broad genera.

5
00:00:37,780 --> 00:00:39,863
that I would now fain put before you.

6
00:00:40,524 --> 00:00:42,106
Yet is it no easy task.

7
00:00:42,587 --> 00:00:47,794
The classification of the constituents of a chaos, nothing less, is here essayed.

8
00:00:48,415 --> 00:00:51,520
Listen to what the best and latest authorities have laid down.

9
00:00:51,780 --> 00:00:58,570
No branch of Zoology is so much involved as that which is entitled Cetology," says Captain Scoresby, A.D.

10
00:00:58,630 --> 00:00:59,451
1820.

11
00:00:59,431 --> 00:01:07,940
It is not my intention, were it in my power, to enter into the inquiry as to the true method of dividing the Cetacea into groups and families.

12
00:01:08,721 --> 00:01:15,248
Utter confusion exists among the historians of this animal hail, says Surgeon Beale, A.D.

13
00:01:15,268 --> 00:01:15,788
1839.

14
00:01:17,250 --> 00:01:20,473
Unfitness to pursue our research in the unfathomable waters.

15
00:01:21,134 --> 00:01:24,357
Impenetrable veil covering our knowledge of the Cetacea.

16
00:01:26,059 --> 00:01:27,801
A field strewn with thorns.

17
00:01:29,232 --> 00:01:33,263
All these incomplete indications but serve to torture us naturalists.

18
00:01:33,283 --> 00:01:41,025
Thus speak of the whale, the great Cuvier, and John Hunter, and lessen those lights of zoology and anatomy.

19
00:01:41,065 --> 00:01:45,216
Nevertheless, though of real knowledge there be little.

20
00:01:45,196 --> 00:01:52,485
Yet of books there are aplenty, and so in some small degree, With cetology or the science of whales.

21
00:01:52,625 --> 00:02:01,256
Many are the men, small and great, old and new, Landsmen and seamen, who had at large or in little Written of the whale.

22
00:02:01,537 --> 00:02:04,080
Run over a few to the authors of the Bible, eh, Aristotle?

23
00:02:04,521 --> 00:02:05,702
Plenty, Aldrovandi.

24
00:02:05,682 --> 00:02:28,956
Sir Thomas Brown Ghesneray Linnaeus Varnetius Willoughby Ginn Green Sir Balde Brison Martin Lassabede Boneteers Dess Marist Byron Cuvier Frederick Cuvier John Hunter Ohm Scoresby Bennett Gross Brown Varthartha Miriam Cuffin Ohms Eid Grev Dijon T. Cheever

25
00:02:28,936 --> 00:02:41,591
But to what ultimate generalizing purpose all these have written, the above-cited extracts will show, of the names in this list of whale authors, only those following Owen ever saw living whales.

26
00:02:42,592 --> 00:02:48,699
And but one of them was a real professional harpooner and whaleman, I mean Captain Scoresby.

27
00:02:49,440 --> 00:02:55,888
On the separate subject of the Greenland, or right whale, he is the best existing authority.

28
00:02:55,868 --> 00:03:04,441
but Scoresby knew nothing, and says nothing of the great sperm-whale, compared with which the Greenland whale is almost unworthy mentioning.

29
00:03:05,262 --> 00:03:11,311
And here be it said that the Greenland whale is an usurper upon the throne of the seas.

30
00:03:12,253 --> 00:03:15,377
He is not even by any means the largest of the whales.

31
00:03:15,578 --> 00:03:21,066
Yet, owing to the long priority of his claims, and the profound ignorance which,

32
00:03:21,046 --> 00:03:38,784
till some seventy years back, invested the then fabulous or utterly unknown sperm-whale, and which, ignorance to this present day, still reigns in all but some few scientific retreats and whale-ports, tis usurpation has been every way complete.

33
00:03:38,804 --> 00:03:50,395
Reference to nearly all the Leviathanic allusions in the great poets of past days will satisfy you that the Greenland whale, without one rival, was to them the monarch of the seas.

34
00:03:50,375 --> 00:03:54,045
But the time has at last come for a new proclamation.

35
00:03:54,667 --> 00:03:56,131
This is Sharing-Cross.

36
00:03:56,612 --> 00:03:59,220
Hear ye, good people, all!

37
00:03:59,260 --> 00:04:02,328
The Greenland whale is deposed.

38
00:04:02,870 --> 00:04:05,397
The great sperm-whale now reigneth.

39
00:04:05,377 --> 00:04:16,060
There are only two books in being which at all pretend to put the living sperm-whale before you, and at the same time, in the remotest degree, succeed in the attempt.

40
00:04:16,080 --> 00:04:25,140
Those books are Beal's and Bennett's, both in their time surgeons to English South Sea whale-ships, and both exact and reliable men.

41
00:04:25,120 --> 00:04:38,997
The original matter touching the sperm-whale to be found in their volumes is necessarily small, but so far as it goes, it is of excellent quality, though mostly confined to scientific description.

42
00:04:39,117 --> 00:04:45,606
As yet, however, the sperm-whale, scientific or poetic, lives not complete in any literature.

43
00:04:46,487 --> 00:04:50,031
Far above all other hunted whales, his is an unwritten life.

44
00:04:50,163 --> 00:05:04,632
Now the various species of whales need some sort of popular, comprehensive classification, if only an easy-outlined one for the present, hereafter to be filled in all its departments by subsequent laborers.

45
00:05:04,953 --> 00:05:08,560
As no better man advances to take this matter in hand,

46
00:05:08,540 --> 00:05:11,443
I hereupon offer my own poor endeavors.

47
00:05:12,385 --> 00:05:20,114
I promise nothing complete, because any human thing supposed to be complete must for that very reason infallibly be faulty.

48
00:05:20,174 --> 00:05:28,243
I shall not pretend to a minute anatomical description of the various species, or in this place at least too much of any description.

49
00:05:29,525 --> 00:05:34,811
My object here is simply to project the draft of a systematization of cetology.

50
00:05:35,952 --> 00:05:38,175
I am the architect, not the builder.

51
00:05:38,155 --> 00:05:54,560
But it is a ponderous task—no ordinary letter-sorter in the post-office is equal to it—to grope down into the bottom of the sea after them, to have one's hands among the unspeakable foundations, ribs, and very pelvis of the world.

52
00:05:55,261 --> 00:05:56,603
This is a fearful thing.

53
00:05:56,803 --> 00:06:00,729
What am I that I should essay to hook the nose of this Leviathan?

54
00:06:01,450 --> 00:06:04,855
The awful tauntings in Job might well appall me.

55
00:06:04,835 --> 00:06:07,900
Will he, the Leviathan, make a covenant with thee?

56
00:06:08,621 --> 00:06:10,524
Behold, the hope of him is vain.

57
00:06:10,844 --> 00:06:14,350
But I have swam through libraries and sailed through oceans.

58
00:06:14,931 --> 00:06:18,236
I have had to do with whales, with these visible hands.

59
00:06:19,097 --> 00:06:21,641
I am in earnest, and I will try.

60
00:06:21,661 --> 00:06:26,168
There are some preliminaries to settle, first soar.

61
00:06:26,148 --> 00:06:37,804
The uncertain, unsettled condition of this science of cytology is in the very vestibule attested by the fact, that in some quarters it still remains a moot point whether a whale be a fish.

62
00:06:38,465 --> 00:06:40,228
In his System of Nature, A.D.

63
00:06:40,248 --> 00:06:49,641
1776, Linnaeus declares, I hereby separate the whales from the fish, but, of my own knowledge, I know that down to the year 1850,

64
00:06:49,891 --> 00:07:00,373
sharks and shad, alewives and herring, against Linnaeus's express edict, were still found dividing the possession of the same seas with the Leviathan.

65
00:07:00,733 --> 00:07:05,122
The grounds upon which Linnaeus would feign have banished the whales from the waters.

66
00:07:05,623 --> 00:07:07,427
He states as follows.

67
00:07:07,407 --> 00:07:21,346
on account of their warm bilocular heart, their lungs, their movable eyelids, their hollow ears, penem interantem feminem mamis lactantem, and, finally, ex legis naturae e gerae marituc.

68
00:07:21,626 --> 00:07:32,301
I submitted all this to my friends, Simeon Macy and Charlie Coffin, of Nantucket, both mess-mates of mine in a certain voyage, and they united in the opinion

69
00:07:32,500 --> 00:07:35,787
that the reasons set forth were altogether insufficient.

70
00:07:36,589 --> 00:07:49,277
Shirley profanely hinted they were humbug, be it known that, waiving all argument, I take the good old-fashioned ground that the whale is a fish, and call upon Holy Jonah to back me.

71
00:07:49,257 --> 00:07:51,540
This fundamental thing settled.

72
00:07:52,141 --> 00:07:57,709
The next point is, in what internal respect does the whale differ from other fish?

73
00:07:58,030 --> 00:08:07,564
Above, Linnaeus has given you those items, but in brief, they are these lungs and warm blood, whereas all other fish are lungless and cold-blooded.

74
00:08:08,145 --> 00:08:16,497
Next case, how shall we define the whale, by his obvious externals, so as conspicuously to label him for all time to come?

75
00:08:16,477 --> 00:08:21,324
To be short, then, a whale is a spouting fish with a horizontal tail.

76
00:08:22,706 --> 00:08:23,507
There you have him.

77
00:08:24,168 --> 00:08:28,454
However contracted, that definition is the result of expanded meditation.

78
00:08:29,415 --> 00:08:35,303
A walrus spouts much like a whale, but the walrus is not a fish, because he is amphibious.

79
00:08:35,403 --> 00:08:41,151
But the last term of the definition is still more cogent, as coupled with the first.

80
00:08:41,131 --> 00:08:58,313
Almost anyone must have noticed that all the fish familiar to landsmen have not a flat, but a vertical or up-and-down tail, whereas among spouting fish the tail, though it may be similarly shaped, invariably assumes a horizontal position.

81
00:08:58,293 --> 00:09:17,723
By the above definition of what a whale is, I do by no means exclude from the Leviathanic Brotherhood any sea creature hitherto identified with the whale by the best-informed Nantucketers, nor, on the other hand, link with it any fish hitherto authoritatively regarded as alien.

82
00:09:18,224 --> 00:09:26,376
For, hence, all the smaller, spouting, and horizontal-tailed fish must be included in this ground plan of cetology.

83
00:09:27,368 --> 00:09:30,651
Now, then, come the grand divisions of the entire whale host.

84
00:09:30,931 --> 00:09:43,764
I am aware that down to the present time the fish-styled llamatins and dugongs, fig-fish and sow-fish, of the coffins of Nantucket, are included by many naturalists among the whales.

85
00:09:43,944 --> 00:09:55,215
But as these big fish are a noisy, contemptible set, mostly lurking in the mouths of rivers and feeding on wet hay, and, especially as they do not spout,

86
00:09:55,195 --> 00:10:02,806
I deny their credentials as whales, and have presented them with their passports to quit the kingdom of cytology.

87
00:10:03,067 --> 00:10:12,861
I. According to magnitude, I divide the whales into three primary books, subdivisible into chapters, and these shall comprehend them all, both small and large.

88
