00:10:18,149 --> 00:10:19,431
The Tordesimu Whale.

94
00:10:19,597 --> 00:10:28,497
As the type of the folio, I present the sperm whale of the octavo, the grampus of the doidecimo, the propoise, folios.

95
00:10:29,058 --> 00:10:37,437
Among these, I here include the following chapters, cacao ma, the sperm whale, and I, the right whale, the finback whale, fine.

96
00:10:37,417 --> 00:10:39,881
Sperm Whale.

97
00:10:40,683 --> 00:10:57,231
This whale, among the English of old, vaguely known as the Trumper Whale, and the Physeter Whale, and the Anvil-Headed Whale, is the present cacalot of the French.

98
00:10:57,700 --> 00:11:02,765
and the Potsvich of the Germans, and the Macrocephalus of the Long Words.

99
00:11:02,945 --> 00:11:21,883
He is, without doubt, the largest inhabitant of the globe, the most formidable of all whales to encounter, the most majestic in aspect, and, lastly, by far the most valuable in commerce, he being the only creature from which that valuable substance, spermaceti, is obtained.

100
00:11:22,444 --> 00:11:27,589
All his peculiarities will, in many other places, be enlarged upon.

101
00:11:27,569 --> 00:11:30,652
It is chiefly with his name that I now have to do.

102
00:11:31,253 --> 00:11:33,875
Philologically considered, it is absurd.

103
00:11:33,895 --> 00:11:57,458
Some centuries ago, when the sperm whale was almost wholly unknown in his own proper individuality, and when his oil was only accidentally obtained from the stranded fish, in those days spermaceti, it would seem, was popularly supposed to be derived from a creature identical with the one then known in England as the Greenland or Right Whale.

104
00:11:57,927 --> 00:12:07,582
It was the idea, also, that this same spermaceti was that quickening humor of the Greenland whale which the first syllable of the word literally expresses.

105
00:12:08,644 --> 00:12:18,059
In those times, also, spermaceti was exceedingly scarce, not being used for light, but only as an ointment and medicament.

106
00:12:18,079 --> 00:12:23,648
It was only to be had from the druggists, as you nowadays buy an ounce of rhubarb.

107
00:12:23,628 --> 00:12:38,811
When, as I opine, in the course of time, the true nature of spermiceti became known, its original name was still retained by the dealers, no doubt to enhance its value by a notion so strangely significant of its scarcity.

108
00:12:39,472 --> 00:12:46,063
And so the appellation must at last have come to be bestowed upon the whale from which this spermiceti was really derived.

109
00:12:47,685 --> 00:12:50,209
Book I Folio, Chapter II

110
00:12:50,712 --> 00:12:59,079
right whale, to live in one respect, this is the most venerable of the leviathans, being the one first regularly hunted by man.

111
00:12:59,280 --> 00:13:08,728
It yields the article commonly known as whale bone or baleen, and the oil specially known as whale oil, an inferior article in commerce.

112
00:13:09,048 --> 00:13:18,897
Among the fishermen, he is indiscriminately designated by all the following titles, the whale, the Greenland, whale, the black whale, the great whale,

113
00:13:18,877 --> 00:13:21,321
The true whale, the right whale.

114
00:13:21,943 --> 00:13:28,434
There is a deal of obscurity concerning the identity of the species thus multitudinously baptized.

115
00:13:29,296 --> 00:13:34,024
What, then, is the whale, which I include in the second species of my folios?

116
00:13:34,545 --> 00:13:41,037
It is the great mysticitous of the English naturalists, the Greenland whale of the English whalemen.

117
00:13:41,017 --> 00:13:47,214
the balien ordinaire of the French whalemen, the groundlands wallfish of the Swedes.

118
00:13:47,414 --> 00:13:54,553
It is the whale which for more than two centuries past has been hunted by the Dutch and English in the Arctic seas.

119
00:13:55,951 --> 00:14:10,547
It is the whale which the American fishermen have long pursued in the Indian Ocean, on the Brazil banks, on the Norwest coast, and various other parts of the world, designated by them Right Whale Cruising Grounds.

120
00:14:10,867 --> 00:14:22,279
Some pretend to see a difference between the Greenland Whale of the English and the Right Whale of the Americans, but they precisely agree in all their grand features,

121
00:14:22,259 --> 00:14:29,587
Nor has there yet been presented a single determinate fact upon which to ground a radical distinction.

122
00:14:30,468 --> 00:14:40,358
It is by endless subdivisions based upon the most inconclusive differences that some departments of natural history become so repellingly intricate.

123
00:14:41,079 --> 00:14:47,566
The right whale will be elsewhere treated of at some length, with reference to elucidating the sperm-whale.

124
00:14:48,207 --> 00:14:49,428
Book I. Folio.

125
00:14:49,648 --> 00:14:50,349
Chapter III.

126
00:14:50,509 --> 00:14:51,270
FINBECK.

127
00:14:51,250 --> 00:15:07,420
Under this head I reckon a monster, which, by the various names of Finback, Talspout, and Long John, has been seen almost in every sea, and is commonly the whale, whose distant jet is so often described by passengers crossing the Atlantic,

128
00:15:07,400 --> 00:15:09,484
in the New York packet tracks.

129
00:15:10,085 --> 00:15:21,225
In the length he attains, and in his baleen, the finback resembles the right whale, but is of a less portly girth, and a lighter colour, approaching to olive.

130
00:15:22,186 --> 00:15:29,239
His great lips present a cable-like aspect, formed by the intertwisting, slanting folds of large wrinkles,

131
00:15:29,219 --> 00:15:36,492
His grand distinguishing feature, the fin from which he derives his name, is often a conspicuous object.

132
00:15:37,033 --> 00:15:47,312
This fin is some three or four feet long, growing vertically from the hinder part of the back, of an angular shape, and with a very sharp pointed end.

133
00:15:47,292 --> 00:15:57,504
Even if not the slightest other part of the creature be visible, this isolated fin will, at times, be seen plainly projecting from the surface.

134
00:15:57,705 --> 00:16:08,878
When the sea is moderately calm and slightly marked with spherical ripples, and this gnomon-like fin stands up and casts shadows upon the wrinkled surface,

135
00:16:08,858 --> 00:16:18,719
It may well be supposed that the watery circle surrounding it somewhat resembles a dial, with its style and wavy hour-lines grained on it.

136
00:16:19,020 --> 00:16:24,792
On that Ahas dial the shadow often goes back, the finback is not gregarious,

137
00:16:24,772 --> 00:16:48,213
He seems a whale-hater, as some men are man-haters, Very shy, always going solitary, Unexpectedly rising to the surface In the remotest and most sullen waters, Hiss straight, and single lofty jet rising Like a tall misanthropic spear upon a barren plain, Gifted with such wondrous power And velocity in swimming, as to defy All present pursuit from man.

138
00:16:48,273 --> 00:16:53,378
This, Leviathan, seems the banished And unconquerable cane of his race,

139
00:16:53,611 --> 00:16:56,095
bearing for his mark that style upon his back.

140
00:16:57,016 --> 00:17:09,797
From having the baleen in his mouth, the finback is sometimes included with the right whale among a theoretic species denominated whale-bone whales, that is, whales with baleen.

141
00:17:09,777 --> 00:17:16,971
Of these so-called whalebone whales, there would seem to be several varieties, most of which, however, are little known.

142
00:17:17,773 --> 00:17:29,355
Broad-nosed whales and beaked whales, pike-headed whales, bunched whales, underjawed whales, and rostrated whales are the fishermen's names for a few sorts.

143
00:17:29,335 --> 00:17:47,901
In connection with this appellative of whale-borne whales, it is of great importance to mention, that however such a nomenclature may be convenient in facilitating allusions to some kind of whales, yet it is in vain to attempt a clear classification of the leviathan, founded upon either his baleen, or hump, or fin, or teeth.

144
00:17:47,881 --> 00:18:09,973
Notwithstanding that those marked parts or features very obviously seem better adapted to afford the basis for a regular system of cytology than any other detached bodily distinctions which the whale in his kinds present, how, then, the baleen, hump, back fin, and teeth, these are things whose peculiarities are indiscriminately dispersed among all sorts of whales,

145
00:18:09,953 --> 00:18:16,604
without any regard to what may be the nature of their structure in other and more essential particulars.

146
00:18:17,064 --> 00:18:23,775
Thus the sperm whale and the humpbacked whale each has a hump but there the similitude ceases.

147
00:18:24,537 --> 00:18:27,962
Then the same humpbacked whale and the Greenland whale

148
00:18:27,942 --> 00:18:36,073
Each of these has baleen, but there again the similitude ceases, and it is just the same with the other parts above mentioned.

149
00:18:36,653 --> 00:18:47,908
In various sorts of whales, they form such irregular combinations, or, in the case of any one of them detached, such an irregular isolation, as utterly

150
00:18:47,888 --> 00:18:52,093
to defy all general methodization formed upon such a basis.

151
00:18:52,314 --> 00:19:07,372
On this rock every one of the whale naturalists has split, but it may possibly be conceived that in the internal parts of the whale, in his anatomy there, at least, we shall be able to hit the right classification.

152
00:19:07,613 --> 00:19:15,162
Nay, what thing, for example, is there in the Greenland whale's anatomy more striking than his baleen?

153
00:19:15,142 --> 00:19:21,433
Yet we have seen that by his baleen it is impossible correctly to classify the Greenland whale.

154
00:19:21,693 --> 00:19:30,028
And if you descend into the bowels, nothing but to take hold of the whale's bodily, in their entire liberal volume, and boldly sort them that way.

155
00:19:30,749 --> 00:19:38,803
And this is the bibliographical system here adopted, and it is the only one that can possibly succeed, for it alone is practicable.

156
00:19:39,205 --> 00:19:39,706
proceed.

157
00:19:40,186 --> 00:19:40,687
FOLIO.

158
00:19:40,987 --> 00:19:41,688
CHAPTER IV.

159
00:19:42,168 --> 00:19:42,909
HUMP BACK.

160
00:19:44,130 --> 00:19:47,013
This whale is often seen on the northern American coast.

161
00:19:47,634 --> 00:19:51,197
He has been frequently captured there and towed into harbor.

162
00:19:51,778 --> 00:19:56,943
He has a great pack on him like a peddler, or you might call him the elephant and castle whale.

163
00:19:57,584 --> 00:20:06,613
At any rate, the popular name for him does not sufficiently distinguish him, since the sperm whale also has a hump, though a smaller one.

164
00:20:06,593 --> 00:20:08,298
His oil is not very valuable.

165
00:20:08,920 --> 00:20:10,083
He has baleen.

166
00:20:10,264 --> 00:20:17,685
He is the most gamesome and light-hearted of all the whales, making more gay foam and white water generally than any other of them.

167
00:20:18,428 --> 00:20:18,949
Book One

168
00:20:19,267 --> 00:20:25,394
FOLIO CHAPTER V RAZOR BACK Of this whale little is known but his name.

169
00:20:26,195 --> 00:20:28,478
I have seen him at a distance off Cape Horn.

170
00:20:28,919 --> 00:20:31,922
Of a retiring nature he eludes both hunters and philosophers.

171
00:20:32,343 --> 00:20:38,090
Though no coward, he has never yet shown any part of him but his back, which rises in a long, sharp ridge.

172
00:20:38,650 --> 00:20:39,211
Let him go.

173
00:20:39,231 --> 00:20:42,675
I know little more of him, nor does anybody else.

174
00:20:44,461 --> 00:21:10,705
