181
00:21:28,141 --> 00:21:40,692
Who, Thesimus, embrace the whales of middling magnitude, among which presently be numbered to I, the grampus says I, the blackfish not too, the nur whale, the thrasher, the fifth, the killer?

182
00:21:40,672 --> 00:22:04,627
Why this Book of Whales is not denominated the Quarto is very plain, because, while the whales of this order, though smaller than those of the former order, nevertheless retain a proportionate likeness to them in figure, yet the Bookbinder's Quarto volume in its dimensioned form does not preserve the shape of the Folio volume, but the Octavo volume does.

183
00:22:05,668 --> 00:22:06,390
Vast Book II.

184
00:22:06,990 --> 00:22:07,631
Octavo.

185
00:22:07,992 --> 00:22:08,653
Chapter 1.

186
00:22:09,214 --> 00:22:10,155
Grampus.

187
00:22:10,135 --> 00:22:22,105
Though this fish, whose loud sonorous breathing, or rather blowing, has furnished a proverb to landsmen, is so well known a denizen of the deep, yet is he not popularly classed among whales.

188
00:22:22,225 --> 00:22:29,131
But, possessing all the grand distinctive features of the Leviathan, most naturalists have recognized him for one.

189
00:22:30,092 --> 00:22:39,400
He is of moderate octavo size, varying from fifteen to twenty-five feet in length, and of corresponding dimensions round the waist.

190
00:22:39,481 --> 00:22:46,423
He swims in herds he has never regularly hunted, though his oil is considerable in quantity and pretty good for light.

191
00:22:47,266 --> 00:22:53,085
By some fishermen his approach is regarded as premonitory of the advance of the great sperm whale.

192
00:22:54,331 --> 00:22:58,081
Black fish!

193
00:22:58,582 --> 00:23:03,836
I give the popular fishermen's names for all these fish, for generally they are the best.

194
00:23:04,458 --> 00:23:10,855
Where any name happens to be vague or inexpressive, I shall say so, and suggest another.

195
00:23:10,835 --> 00:23:17,386
I do so now, touching the black fish, so called, because blackness is the rule among almost all whales.

196
00:23:18,507 --> 00:23:21,152
So, call him the Hyena Whale, if you please.

197
00:23:21,332 --> 00:23:32,570
His voracity is well known, and from the circumstance that the inner angles of his lips are curved upwards, he carries an everlasting Mephistophelian grin on his face.

198
00:23:33,332 --> 00:23:37,939
This whale averages some sixteen or eighteen feet in length.

199
00:23:37,919 --> 00:23:40,441
He is found in almost all latitudes.

200
00:23:40,581 --> 00:23:48,048
He has a peculiar way of showing his dorsal hooked fin in swimming, which looks something like a Roman nose.

201
00:23:48,228 --> 00:24:07,926
When not more profitably employed, the sperm whale hunters sometimes capture the hyena whale to keep up the supply of cheap oil for domestic employment as some frugal housekeepers, in the absence of company, and quite alone by themselves burn unsavory tallow instead of odorous wax.

202
00:24:07,906 --> 00:24:13,553
Though their blubber is very thin, some of these whales will yield you upwards of thirty gallons of oil.

203
00:24:14,694 --> 00:24:21,183
Book 2 Octabo Chapter 3 Narhal, that is, Nostril Whale.

204
00:24:21,923 --> 00:24:29,813
Another instance of a curiously named whale, so named, I suppose, from his peculiar horn, being originally mistaken for a peaked nose.

205
00:24:29,973 --> 00:24:32,817
The creature is some sixteen feet in length.

206
00:24:32,797 --> 00:24:39,488
while its horn averages five feet, though some exceed ten, and even attain to fifteen feet.

207
00:24:40,489 --> 00:24:48,662
Strictly speaking, this horn is but a lengthened tusk, growing out from the jaw in a line a little depressed from the horizontal.

208
00:24:48,642 --> 00:24:58,334
but it is only found on the sinister side, which has an ill effect, giving its owner something analogous to the aspect of a clumsy left-handed man.

209
00:24:59,356 --> 00:25:04,643
What precise purpose this ivory horn or lance answers, it would be hard to say.

210
00:25:04,883 --> 00:25:18,160
It does not seem to be used like the blade of the swordfish and billfish, though some sailors tell me that the narwhal employs it for a rake in turning over the bottom of the sea for food.

211
00:25:18,140 --> 00:25:31,365
Charlie Coffin said it was used for an ice-piercer for the narwhal rising to the surface of the polar sea and finding it sheeted with ice, thrusts his horn up and so breaks through.

212
00:25:32,207 --> 00:25:35,794
But you cannot prove either of these surmises to be correct.

213
00:25:35,774 --> 00:25:48,398
My own opinion is that however this one-sided horn may really be used by the narwhal, however, that may be it, would certainly be very convenient to him for a folder in reading pamphlets.

214
00:25:49,540 --> 00:25:55,251
The narwhal I have heard called the tusked whale, the horned whale, and the unicorn whale.

215
00:25:55,315 --> 00:26:02,587
He is certainly a curious example of the unicornism to be found in almost every kingdom of animated nature.

216
00:26:03,168 --> 00:26:17,931
From certain cloistered old authors I have gathered that this same sea-unicorn's horn was in ancient days regarded as the great antidote against poison, and, as such, preparations of it brought immense prices.

217
00:26:17,911 --> 00:26:26,559
It was also distilled to abolital salts for fainting ladies, the same way that the horns of the male deer are manufactured into heart's horn.

218
00:26:27,520 --> 00:26:32,444
Originally it was in itself a counted and object of great curiosity.

219
00:26:32,544 --> 00:26:46,197
Black letter tells me that Sir Martin Frobisher, on his return from that voyage, when Queen Bess did gallantly wave her jeweled hand to him from a window of Gurnidge Palace, as his bold ship sailed down the Thames,

220
00:26:46,177 --> 00:27:00,338
When Sir Martin returned from that voyage, saith Blackletter, on bended knees he presented to Her Highness a prodigious long horn of the Nurwell, which, for a long period after, hung in the castle at Windsor.

221
00:27:01,921 --> 00:27:14,248
An Irish author avers that the Earl of Leicester, on bended knees, did likewise present to Her Highness another horn, pertaining to a land-beast of the unicorn nature.

222
00:27:14,268 --> 00:27:19,980
The narwhal has a very picturesque, leopard-like look, being of a milk-white grand colour,

223
00:27:19,960 --> 00:27:23,147
dotted with round and oblong spots of black.

224
00:27:23,949 --> 00:27:30,023
His oil is very superior, clear and fine, but there is little of it, and he is seldom hunted.

225
00:27:30,745 --> 00:27:36,518
He is mostly found in the circumpolar seas.

226
00:27:37,983 --> 00:27:45,413
KILLER Of this whale little is precisely known to the Ned Tucketer, and nothing at all to the professed Naturalist.

227
00:27:46,214 --> 00:27:51,201
From what I have seen of him at a distance, I should say that he was about the bigness of a Grampus.

228
00:27:51,301 --> 00:27:53,785
He is very savage, a sort of Fiji fish.

229
00:27:54,466 --> 00:28:02,657
He sometimes takes the great folio whales by the lip, and hangs there like a leech, till the mighty brute is worried to death.

230
00:28:02,637 --> 00:28:04,540
The killer is never hunted.

231
00:28:05,081 --> 00:28:07,265
I never heard what sort of oil he has.

232
00:28:07,305 --> 00:28:18,202
Exception might be taken to the name bestowed upon this whale, on the ground of its indistinctness, for we are all killers, on land and on sea, Bonapartes and sharks included.

233
00:28:18,803 --> 00:28:19,785
Book Two

234
00:28:19,765 --> 00:28:20,626
OCAVO.

235
00:28:21,127 --> 00:28:22,730
CHAPTER V. THRASHER.

236
00:28:23,291 --> 00:28:28,639
This gentleman is famous for his tail, which he uses for a ferule in thrashing his foes.

237
00:28:29,381 --> 00:28:39,998
He mounts the folio whale's back, and as he swims he works his passage by flogging him, as some schoolmasters get along in the world by a similar process.

238
00:28:40,398 --> 00:28:43,343
Still less is known of the thrasher than of the killer,

239
00:28:43,323 --> 00:28:45,787
Both are outlaws, even in the lawless seas.

240
00:28:46,168 --> 00:28:47,270
Thus ends Book Two.

241
00:28:48,151 --> 00:28:49,954
Octavo, and begins Book Three.

242
00:28:50,656 --> 00:28:51,798
Duodecimo.

243
00:28:51,818 --> 00:28:53,220
These include the smaller whales.

244
00:28:54,062 --> 00:28:55,744
I, the Husa porpoise.

245
00:28:55,765 --> 00:28:57,387
II, the Algerine porpoise.

246
00:28:57,908 --> 00:29:01,855
III, the mealy-mouthed porpoise.

247
00:29:01,835 --> 00:29:18,679
To those who have not chanced specially to study the subject, it may possibly seem strange that fishes not commonly exceeding four or five feet should be marshalled among whale as a word, which, in the popular sense, always conveys an idea of hugeness.

248
00:29:18,659 --> 00:29:29,232
But the creatures set down above, as duodecimos, are infallibly whales, by the terms of my definition of what a whale is, i.e., a spouting fish, with a horizontal tail.

249
00:29:30,177 --> 00:29:32,247
Book 3 DUODECIMO

